                <!-- D/JQA/24.1220 -->

                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-01">
                    <head>1 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-01"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <dateline><hi rend="italic">February 1798.</hi></dateline>
                        <p><date>1. </date>Tea this Evening at the <persRef ref="schultz-carl">Baron
                                Schulz von Ascheraden’s</persRef>, with <persRef ref="u">his
                                sister</persRef>, a maiden Lady who lives with him. Company small.
                                <persRef ref="u">Madame de Carisien</persRef> widow of the <persRef
                                ref="voncarisien-carl">late Swedish Minister</persRef> and a
                                <persRef ref="u">Chevalier de Bressac</persRef>; a french
                            Neapolitan— Little exercise of late from having much writing.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-02">
                    <head>2 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-02"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="210" type="ms"/>
                        <p><date>2. </date>Spent the day at home. Writing in the former part of it.
                            Began reading <persRef ref="imlay-gilbert">Imlay’s</persRef> Account of the Western
                            Country of America— Evening reading of Geography, and <persRef
                                ref="thomson-james">Thomson’s</persRef> Liberty; a dull Poem.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-03">
                    <head>3 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-03"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                        <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>3. </date>Evening at <persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp">Baron
                                Alvensleben’s</persRef> assembly: not a Ball. That amusement is
                            suspended by the illness of the <persRef
                                ref="frederick-william-iii;louiseauguste">king &amp;
                            queen</persRef>, both of whom have the measles; as also the <persRef
                                ref="frederica-sophia">Princess Louis</persRef>, &amp; <persRef
                                    ref="wilhelmina2">Princess of Orange</persRef>. Play’d
                            Whist, with <persRef ref="u">Madame de Molcke</persRef>, <persRef
                                ref="u">Madame de Wulknitz</persRef> &amp; <persRef
                                ref="vonzastrow-alexander">M. Zastrow</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-04">
                    <head>4 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-04"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>4. </date>Day chiefly at home. <persRef ref="u"
                                >Mademoiselle de Schultz</persRef> called and took tea with <persRef
                                ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
                            <persRef ref="schultz-carl">Her brother</persRef> is very unwell this
                            day.— I have been writing some Letters, but find myself still too often
                            interupted.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-05">
                    <head>5 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-05"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                        <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>5. </date>At the <persRef ref="wilhelminaofhesse">Princess
                                Henry’s</persRef> at the beginning of the Evening. <persRef
                                ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A</persRef>.
                            stayed there to supper; for by the peculiar usages of this Court the
                            wives of foreign Ministers are expected to sup with the Princesses,
                            although the Ministers themselves are not. The reason is that the Ladies
                            have no rank, and there can be no dispute for precedence between them—
                            Met <persRef ref="vonthulemeyer-friedrich">M. de Thulemeyer</persRef>,
                            for the first time, and recognized him.— Came away as the Princess sat
                            down to cards, and went to <persRef ref="augustusferdinand">Prince
                                Ferdinand’s</persRef>, where we had a special invitation for this
                            Evening.— Whist with <persRef ref="u">Madam de Bredow</persRef>.
                                <persRef ref="u">Madame de Massow</persRef>, and the <persRef
                                ref="neale-ferdinand">Count Neale</persRef>.— Came home before
                            supper.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-06">
                    <head>6 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-06"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>6. </date><persRef ref="neale-pauline">M<hi rend="superscript">lle.</hi> de
                                Neale</persRef> and <persRef ref="deberg-louisa">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >lle:</hi> de Berg</persRef>, called this forenoon upon <persRef
                                ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>—
                            Wrote a letter to <persRef ref="adams-abigail">my mother</persRef>.—
                            Evening at home.— Geography. 4<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> part of <persRef
                                ref="thomson-james">Thomson’s</persRef> Liberty. Nothing in it to
                            give an interest.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-07">
                    <head>7 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-07"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>7. </date>Walk with <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef> and a long one alone. Evening
                            at <persRef ref="vonzinzendorf-friedrich">Count Zinzendorff’s</persRef>
                            who had a tea and card party. Some conversation with <persRef
                                ref="haugwitz-christian">Count Haugwitz</persRef>. Reversi with
                                <persRef ref="u">Madame de Haaren</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">lle:</hi> Dorville</persRef>, and a frenchman
                                <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Dubois</persRef>.— Home
                            soon after 9.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-08">
                    <head>8 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-08"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>8. </date>The day and evening at home, excepting the usual walks.
                            Finished <persRef ref="thomson-james">Thomson’s</persRef> poor Poem of
                            Liberty. Some Geography. There is a great sameness in the mode of
                            passing time when we are once settled.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-09">
                    <head>9 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-09"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>9. </date>Evening at a tea and card party at the <persRef
                                ref="vonheinitz-friedrich">Baron Heinitz’s</persRef>. He has them
                            weekly. These parties all have a great resemblance to one another, and
                            you meet at them nearly the same company. They assemble between 6 and 7
                            in the Evening; in a suite of four or five rooms containing each as many
                            card tables. Every person is to make up his own party for play, which is
                            usually Cassino, Ombre, Whist or Reversi. They play till about 9 and
                            soon after all the company retire.— Play’d Whist, with the <persRef
                                ref="u">Countess de Keyserling</persRef>, the <persRef ref="u"
                                >Marquis de S<hi rend="superscript">t:</hi> Vincent</persRef>, and a
                                <persRef ref="gallatin-pierre">Chevalier de Gallatin</persRef>, who
                            enquired of me about <persRef ref="gallatin-albert">his
                                namesake</persRef> in America.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-10">
                    <head>10 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-10"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>10. </date>Weather dull, rainy, windy; resembling the ordinary
                            winter weather— Evening at <persRef ref="alvensleben-philipp">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">r:</hi> Alvensleben’s.</persRef> the last of his six
                            weekly assemblies. Reversi with <persRef ref="u">Madame de
                                Haaren</persRef>, <persRef ref="muzquiz-ignacio">M.
                                Musquitz</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">M: de Wulknitz</persRef>.—
                                <persRef ref="u">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Knoblauch</persRef> the
                            Danish chargé des affairs says that the Young <persRef
                                ref="bernstorff-christian">Count de Bernstorff</persRef> is <hi
                                rend="italic">Secretary of</hi> State, and at the head of the
                            department of foreign affairs. But not Minister of State; which is an
                            higher rank.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-11">
                    <head>11 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-11"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>11. </date>Day at home. Weather very bad. Finished <persRef
                                ref="imlay-gilbert">Imlay’s</persRef> great hotch-pot about America,
                            and commenced upon <persRef ref="washington-george">General
                                Washington’s</persRef> official Letters, which I have never
                            regularly read. Evening Geography, and the first Canto of <persRef
                                ref="thomson-james">Thomson’s</persRef> Castle of Indolence a very
                            agreeable Poem, though its plan has not sufficient method for so long a
                            work.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-12">
                    <head>12 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-12"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>12. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> very unwell: so that she could not go
                            out.— Evening at the <persRef ref="wilhelminaofhesse">Princess
                                Henry’s</persRef>. Whist with the <persRef ref="haugwitz-johanna"
                                >Countess Haugwitz</persRef>, <persRef ref="u">Madame de
                                Moltke</persRef> and <persRef ref="u">M. de Knoblauch</persRef>, the
                            Danish chargé des affairs.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-13">
                    <head>13 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-13"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Health and Illness</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="211" type="ms"/>
                        <p><date>13. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> continues very unwell, so as to give
                            me extreme anxiety and alarm.— Wrote to <persRef ref="murray-william2"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Murray.</persRef> At the Cassino in the
                            afternoon. Evening read the remainder of <persRef ref="thomson-james"
                                >Thomson’s</persRef> Castle of Indolence.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-14">
                    <head>14 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-14"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>14. </date>Day again at home. Letter to <persRef
                                ref="adams-charles">My Brother Charles</persRef>. <persRef
                                ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi>
                                Adams</persRef> still unwell. Walk before dinner— Read all <persRef
                                ref="thomson-james">Thomson’s</persRef> short Poems, all of which
                            are pleasing.— Geography Preface to <persRef ref="walsh-william"
                                >Walsh’s</persRef> Poems.— Thomson used to consider his Liberty as
                            his most valuable Poem.— <persRef ref="milton-john">Milton</persRef>
                            gave a similar preference to his Paradise regained.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-15">
                    <head>15 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-15"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>15. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> yet unwell— Home the day through.
                            Reading <persRef ref="washington-george">Washington’s</persRef> official
                            Letters: my Geography, and part of <persRef ref="shakespeare-william"
                                >Shakespeare’s</persRef> tempest.— Admitted this Evening as a member
                            of the Casino. No writing. My time not employed with sufficient
                            industry.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-16">
                    <head>16 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-16"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>16. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> Adams</persRef> was apparently well again all the
                            former part of the day; but in the Evening— Our hopes were raised merely
                            to be more severely dashed to the ground.— Dined with the <persRef
                                ref="danadia-joao">Vicomte d’Anadia</persRef>, the Portuguese
                            Minister— A very splendid dinner.— Company about twenty-five persons.—
                            Interesting conversation with the <persRef ref="muzquiz-ignacio">Marquis
                                de Musquitz</persRef> &amp; with <persRef ref="u">Captain de
                                Knoblauch</persRef> the Danish chargé des affairs.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-17">
                    <head>17 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-17"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>17. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">My wife</persRef>
                            yet very ill.— Wrote a letter in the forenoon. Evening a short time at
                            the <persRef ref="hordt-sophia">Countess Hordt’s</persRef>, where there
                            was a large party— I stayed but about half an hour. There was a Ball to
                            at <persRef ref="u">Count Wingersky’s</persRef>, which I did not
                            attend.— I learn nothing.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-18">
                    <head>18 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-18"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                        <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>18. </date>Walk this forenoon in the Park.— <persRef ref="u">The
                                Abbé de Bissi</persRef> called to see me this afternoon— He is a man
                            of some understanding and information.— Evening at <persRef
                                ref="augustusferdinand">Prince Ferdinand’s</persRef>. <persRef
                                ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
                            could not go, being still quite unwell.— Whist with the <persRef
                                ref="haugwitz-johanna">Countess Haugwitz</persRef>, <persRef
                                ref="konigsdorf-luisa">Countess Königsdorff</persRef> &amp; <persRef
                                ref="u">Count Kielmanusegg</persRef>—the party was larger than
                            usual— Appointment to call on <persRef ref="haugwitz-christian">Count
                                Haugwitz</persRef> at 5 to morrow afternoon. Did not stay to
                            supper.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-19">
                    <head>19 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-19"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>19. </date>Called upon <persRef ref="haugwitz-christian">Count
                                Haugwitz</persRef> this afternoon according to appointment.
                            Conversation with him principally upon the late french decree against
                            neutral navigation.— My correspondence contains its substance. I shall
                            see him again. Evening at home writing to the <persRef
                                ref="pickering-timothy">Secretary of State</persRef> &amp;c.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-20">
                    <head>20 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-20"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>20. </date>Went this morning to look out for lodgings. We are to
                            quit those which we now hold on the first of May. Saw two houses neither
                            of which will suit us.— There appear to be no convenient, though great
                            abundance of magnificent houses at Berlin.— Dined with <persRef ref="u"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Schickler</persRef> at 1. Company of
                            about twenty persons as usual. The Swedish <persRef ref="u">Count
                                Gyldenstolpe</persRef> &amp; the <persRef ref="vonompteda-ludwig"
                                >Baron d’Ompteda</persRef> were among them. We came away at about 4.
                            This is the general custom here.— Evening reading at home.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-21">
                    <head>21 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-21"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date><hi rend="strikethrough">24.</hi> 21. </date><persRef
                                ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef>
                            again unwell.— Writing as much as I can— Walk before dinner. At the
                            Casino, in the Evening. Latter part of it at home, alone and
                            unhappy.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-22">
                    <head>22 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-22"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>22. </date><persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi rend="superscript"
                                    >rs:</hi> A.</persRef> again better, to flatter us again, and
                            make the curse more bitter. Ball this evening at <persRef
                                ref="vonfinckenstein-karl">Count Finckenstein’s</persRef>. Went
                            there for a few minutes; but soon returned to my anxious home.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-23">
                    <head>23 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-23"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>23. </date>A short walk in the forenoon and wrote a couple of
                            Letters.— Afternoon at the Casino. Evening at home; finished the little
                            course of Geography, and also <persRef ref="washington-george">General
                                Washington’s</persRef> Official Letters.— Reading likewise, <persRef
                                ref="shakespeare-william">Shakspeare’s</persRef> plays.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-24">
                    <head>24 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-24"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <pb n="212" type="ms"/>
                        <p><date>24. </date>Rainy day. Wrote a long letter to the <persRef
                                ref="adams-john">President</persRef>. Short walk after dinner and an
                            hour at the Casino.— Reading <persRef ref="shakespeare-william"
                                >Shakspeare</persRef> in the Evening— Began for morning reading the
                            Memoir’s and Letters of <persRef ref="lee-charles">General
                            Lee</persRef>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-25">
                    <head>25 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-25"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>25. </date>This morning a letter, which should have gone a
                            fortnight ago, to the Post-Office, was brought here by a soldier who
                            said he had found it in the Street open, and finding it in English had
                            after some fruitless enquiries to whom it belonged, carried it to
                                <persRef ref="bruce-thomas">Lord Elgin’s</persRef> from whence he
                            was immediately sent with it here. Upon enquiry I found that Frederic to
                            whom it had been given on the 10<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> to carry to the
                            Post-Office, had given it to one of his comrades who offered to carry it
                            for him; but who pocketed the money given him to frank it, and kept the
                            letter untill this morning when he lost it in the street.— This is the
                            story with which I must now content myself. The letter was not very
                            important; but it impresses the absolute necessity of two cautionary
                            rules. The one that nothing must be written without attention to the
                            chance of its being intercepted: and the other that none but a
                            confidential person <hi rend="italic">must</hi> be entrusted with
                            letters to be delivered at the Post-Office— I have not indeed at this
                            time to learn either of these maxims; but it is almost impossible to
                            have an unceasing attention even to principles of which the application
                            daily recurs.— Walk out just before dinner; met <persRef
                                ref="garlike-benjamin">M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Garlike</persRef>,
                            secretary of the British legation, who said the soldier came this
                            morning before he was out of bed, with the letters which the servants
                            told him must belong to me, and which he told them to bring over to me,
                            but did not see them.— There was one to <persRef ref="williams-samuel2"
                                    >M<hi rend="superscript">r:</hi> Williams</persRef> &amp; one to the
                                <persRef ref="pickering-timothy">Secretary of State</persRef> of the
                                10<hi rend="superscript">th:</hi> inst<hi rend="superscript">t:</hi>— Both had been
                            enclosed under a cover to Williams, which was taken off and has not been
                            returned.— Evening at home.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-26">
                    <head>26 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-26"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
                    <subject>Court Life and Society (European)</subject>
                        <subject>Recreation</subject>
                    </bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>26. </date>Undertaking to write, what I shall probably never
                            finish.— Dined with <persRef ref="bruce-thomas">Lord Elgin</persRef>.—
                            Company not numerous.— Evening at the <persRef ref="wilhelminaofhesse"
                                >Princess Henry’s</persRef>.— Reversi, with the <persRef ref="georgeofmecklenburg"
                                >Prince of Mecklenburg</persRef>, <persRef ref="riedesel-charlotte"
                                >Madame de Riedesel</persRef>, and the <persRef ref="reuss-augusta"
                                >Countess Reuss</persRef>.— Lord Elgin asked whether I had made any
                            representations here upon the late french decree against neutral
                            Navigation. The Danish <persRef ref="u">Chargé d’Affaires</persRef> had
                            he said, and remonstrances from this Court had been made at Paris, but
                            no answer yet received.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-27">
                    <head>27 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-27"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>27. </date>Rose very late, having been disturbed in the night—
                            Wrote a little in the morning. An hour in the afternoon at the Casino—
                            The plan which I hinted at yesterday and at the execution of which I
                            employed a little more time this morning, already presents difficulties
                            which I fear will prove insuperable.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-28">
                    <head>28 February 1798</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02-28"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date>28. </date>Walk with <persRef ref="adams-louisa-catherine">M<hi
                                    rend="superscript">rs:</hi> A.</persRef> in the alley of lime trees; and
                            afterwards a short one alone. Continued writing; but not to my
                            satisfaction. Reading <persRef ref="shakespeare-william"
                                >Shakespeare</persRef> in the Evening.</p>

                    </div>
                </div>
                <div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v24-1798-02-xx">
                    <head>Day</head>
                    <bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1798-02"/><editor
                            role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor></bibl>
                    <div type="docbody">
                        <p><date><hi rend="italic">Day</hi>.</date> Rise usually at 7. Read till 9.
                            Breakfast. Read. Write &amp;c till 2. Walk from thence untill 3. Dine.—
                            Converse or dress to go out untill 6 or 7. Evening either out, in
                            company or at home reading untill 9 or 10. Supper and soon after 10. to
                            bed.— This life is regular enough: but not altogether such as pleases
                            myself.— After finishing <persRef ref="dupratz-antoine">Du page du
                                pratz’s</persRef> History of Louisiana, I read <persRef
                                ref="imlay-gilbert">Imlay’s</persRef> compilation, which was
                            followed by <persRef ref="washington-george">General
                                Washington’s</persRef> Official Letters, and these, by <persRef
                                ref="lee-charles">Lee’s</persRef> memoir’s and Letters, which I
                            propose finishing to-morrow.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
